Oil is an age old remedy used for all types of hair conditions, but using it in certain conditions may worsen the situation

In no ways am I saying that oiling is bad just in few conditions it can lead to hairfall 
So the great old sayings about oiling hair can cure all hair issues is not true 

DANDRUFF 

The yeast that causes dandruff feasts on the saturated fatty acids found in oils like coconut and olive. A study revealed that researchers who wanted to grow this yeast used olive oil for fulfilling their purpose. So applying oil on an infected scalp may accelerate the hair fall process

ACNE
the oil can find its way to your skin. Once this happens, the oil can clog your pores. Clogged pores can lead to acne.
These can appear along your hairline, forehead, or the back of your neck.

EXCESSIVE HAIRFALL 
When your hair and scalp are overly greasy. Although this seems harmless, excess oil can clog pores on your scalp which can prevent your hair follicles from growing normally! And as a result, you may experience rapid hair loss.

While oiling can be beneficial In
- boosting blood circulation
- strengthening  roots
- promoting hair growth
It is important to know that it should not be done in dandruff or oily scalp
And only done 2-3 times a month 
Only kept for 1-2 hours before the wash

🏊‍♀️ Skincare Tips for Swimming in Summers

1. Pre-Swim Protection

• Apply Moisturizer: Use a moisturizer before swimming to create a barrier between your skin and chlorine or saltwater. This helps protect your skin’s natural barrier. 🧴

• Apply Waterproof Sunscreen: Use a broad-spectrum sunscreen with SPF 30 or higher, even if it’s waterproof. Reapply every two hours. ☀️

• Protect Your Hair: Wear a swim cap to minimize exposure to chlorinated water, which can dry out hair. 🩲

2. Post-Swim Care

• Rinse Immediately: After swimming, rinse off with fresh water to remove chlorine or saltwater, which can dry and irritate skin. 🚿

• Moisturize: Apply a hydrating moisturizer to replenish lost moisture. Look for products with ingredients like hyaluronic acid or aloe vera. 💧

• Condition Hair: Use a nourishing conditioner or hair mask to restore moisture and prevent damage from chlorine. 🌊

3. Skin Repair and Hydration

• Hydrate Inside Out: Drink plenty of water to keep skin hydrated from within. 🥤

• After-Sun Care: Use after-sun products containing soothing ingredients like cucumber or chamomile to calm irritated skin. 🌿

4. Protect Lips and Eyes

• Lip Balm: Apply a lip balm with SPF to protect lips from sun and wind exposure. 💋

• Sunglasses: Wear UV-protective sunglasses to shield your eyes from harmful UV rays. 🕶️

5. Skincare Routine Maintenance

• Gentle Cleansing: Use a gentle cleanser to remove chlorine, salt, and sweat without stripping natural oils. 🧼

• Exfoliate Weekly: Exfoliate once a week to remove dead skin cells and prevent clogged pores caused by sunscreen and sweat buildup. ✨
	6.	Healthy Diet

	•	Eat Antioxidant-Rich Foods: Include fruits and vegetables rich in antioxidants like berries, tomatoes, and leafy greens to protect skin from sun damage. 🍓🥗

Remember, consistent skincare and hydration are key to maintaining healthy skin while swimming in the summer months. Enjoy your swim while keeping your skin protected and nourished! 🌞💦 #SummerSkincare #SwimmingTips #HealthySkin
